{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Q5YEfrw6zSQSEiBG8Lt8W7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me understand the task:\n\n1. Deploy a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster in the `elasticsearch` namespace\n2. Use native Kubernetes resources only (no CRDs/operators)\n3. Use image `docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:8.11.1`\n4. TLS secret `es-http-tls` already exists with `tls.crt`, `tls.key`, and `ca.crt`\n5. Password secret `elastic-password` already exists with key `password`\n\nI need to:\n- Create a ConfigMap with the Elasticsearch configuration, setting up the cluster name, node discovery, and TLS settings for both HTTP and transport layers\n- Set up a StatefulSet with 3 replicas that mounts the config and secrets\n- Create a headless Service for internal pod-to-pod communication\n- Create a regular Service named `es-http` for external access with TLS\n\nNow I'm thinking through the security setup for Elasticsearch 8.x. Since security is enabled by default, I need to configure TLS for both the HTTP API and inter-node transport communication. The `es-http-tls` secret provides the certificate and key for HTTP, and I'll need to decide whether to use the same certificate for transport or generate a separate one based on the SANs in the certificate.\n\nConfiguring transport TLS... I could set `verification_mode: certificate` to verify the cert signature without checking hostnames, which would work since all nodes share the same CA. I'm now sketching out the Kubernetes services needed—a headless service for discovery and an HTTP service for client access.\n\nWriting service definitions... Writing config YAML... Writing Kubernetes manifest...\n\nI'm realizing the task description says these resources don't exist yet, so I need to create them all. For Elasticsearch 8.x, I should set the heap size with `ES_JAVA_OPTS` and handle the elastic user password through environment variables. I also need an init container to fix permissions on the data directory since Elasticsearch runs as UID 1000.\n\nFor cluster discovery, the pods will be named `es-0`, `es-1`, `es-2` and accessible through the headless service. I should use the fully qualified DNS names like `es-0.es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` for `discovery.seed_hosts` to be safe, and `cluster.initial_master_nodes` needs to match the actual node names exactly, which will come from the `NODE_NAME` environment variable.\n\nI'm also considering the JVM heap size for resource constraints and whether to add a PodDisruptionBudget—it's good practice for production even if not explicitly required. Since Elasticsearch 8.x has security enabled by default, I need to handle TLS configuration for the transport layer.\n\nThe `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting only applies during initial bootstrap, so restarting pods won't cause issues once the cluster is formed. I'll use `volumeClaimTemplates` in the StatefulSet to ensure data persistence across pod restarts. Let me now write out the complete YAML, keeping in mind the existing resources: the `elasticsearch` namespace, the TLS secret `es-http-tls` with certificate files, and the `elastic-password` secret.\n\nI need to create a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration, a headless Service for node discovery, the `es-http` Service for HTTP access, a StatefulSet with 3 replicas, and optionally a PodDisruptionBudget. For Elasticsearch 8.x with security enabled, I'll set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable from the secret to configure the built-in `elastic` user. For heap sizing, I'll let Elasticsearch handle it automatically based on available memory, though I could constrain it if needed.\n\nWriting the Kubernetes manifests... Configuring SSL/TLS certificates for both HTTP and transport layer security, then setting up the headless service...\n\nNow I'm defining the HTTP service to expose Elasticsearch on port 9200, and creating a StatefulSet with three replicas for the cluster.\n\nSetting up pod template... Configuring resource limits and requests for memory, setting up volumes from the config map and TLS secret, defining persistent storage with a 10Gi claim template, and adding a pod disruption budget to ensure at least 2 replicas stay available during cluster maintenance. I'm reconsidering the readiness probe logic to make sure it's checking the cluster health correctly. Completing the readiness probe with a health check that queries the cluster status. I'm also reconsidering the init container setup since Elasticsearch 8.x runs as UID 1000 and might have permission issues with mounted PVCs, plus I need to account for the `vm.max_map_count` sysctl requirement that Elasticsearch enforces.\n\nAdding an init container to increase the vm.max_map_count to 262144 using a privileged busybox container, though this might already be set in kind clusters. Now I'm thinking through the resource allocation for a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster on kind.\n\nFor the probes, I'll set up a readiness check that verifies cluster health is yellow or green, and a liveness probe using a TCP check on port 9200 to ensure the process is running. Refining the liveness probe approach...\n\nI'm simplifying the check to just verify the HTTP status code—either 200 for a successful response or 401 for an unauthenticated request, both indicating Elasticsearch is running and responding to requests.\n\nNow I need to think through the full cluster configuration, particularly around service discovery. With a headless service, Kubernetes DNS will automatically resolve all pod IPs, so I can reference the service name directly rather than listing individual pod FQDNs. The key is enabling `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` on the headless service so pods can discover each other during the initial bootstrap phase before they're fully ready.\n\nFor the node naming, Elasticsearch supports environment variable substitution in its config file using `${VAR_NAME}` syntax, so I can inject the pod name via the `NODE_NAME` environment variable. Since StatefulSet pods are named predictably (`es-0`, `es-1`, `es-2`), these will match what I specify in `cluster.initial_master_nodes`. I should also add a PodDisruptionBudget with `minAvailable: 2` to protect the 3-node cluster during maintenance.\n\nWriting the final manifest...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11826,"cache_read_input_tokens":16950,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11826},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"51f6d2b1-a34d-4f3d-8926-cb63d50c2a82","uuid":"dffa13f9-60db-4d5c-bf21-9d1e2cbbfe71","request_id":"req_011CcP2K5SZEHngVvgT5XB2k"}
